ACUTE FEBRILE DISEASE - MALDIVES: (LAAMU ATOLL) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Tue 13 Jan 2009
Source: Minivan News [edited]
<http://www.minivannews.com/news_detail.php?id=5842>


The outbreak of chikungunya, viral fever, and dengue fever on several
islands in Laamu Atoll has been described as an "epidemic" by the deputy
director of L Gan Hospital. Ali Nasir said the outbreak began around a
month ago [December 2008] on Isdhoo-Kalaidhoo before spreading to several
other islands including Fonadhoo and Gaadhoo. He said although the problem
was an annual occurrence, "this year is worse than before" as "more than
1000 people have been affected."

Nasir explained the situation could be described as an epidemic as 10
people were being diagnosed with one of the 3 diseases on a daily basis,
although very few had contracted dengue.

But 2 employees at the health centre at Isdhoo-Kalaidhoo have said the
figure was closer to around 25 to 30 a day. Dr Kiran Singh, an Indian
doctor at the health centre, has said although he would not refer to the
situation as an epidemic, the number was steadily increasing. "In total
there are 25 people coming from morning to evening."

A community worker at the health centre, Adam Moosa, blamed the outbreak on
mosquitoes. He said the problem had begun over a month ago but had
deteriorated and there were currently, "30 people coming daily." But, he
said, only up to 6 people could be admitted at any one time because of the
number of beds at the health centre.

Mohamed Latheef, an Isdhoo Island office employee, said the lack of
resources was making it difficult to deal with the problem effectively. "We
need materials and equipment," he said. "Medicine is also a problem and
there is not enough staff."

According to Nasir, the hospital is taking preventative measures to see to
the outbreak. "Every day we are sending teams to the islands to spray
mosquito areas and along with that we are cleaning islands with the help of
people."

[byline: Maryam Omidi]

--
communicated by:
