<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not possible to determine from this report how many of the febrile
cases are due to chikungunya or dengue virus infections or to viral fever,
the etiology of which is not defined. There is no indication that
laboratory diagnosis of any of these cases has been made. In 2006 there was
a major chikungunya outbreak in the Maldives (ProMED-mail archive no.
20061224.3598). There was a single chikungunya case imported into Singapore
from the Maldives in September 2008, and a 1 Jun 2008 report of both
chikungunya and dengue virus outbreaks occurring on the Maldives
(ProMED-mail archive no. 20080618.1901), so it is certainly possible that
both of these viruses are being transmitted on the island chain currently.
ProMED-mail requests additional information about the diagnoses of these
cases as it becomes available.

A map showing the location of the Maldive Islands in the Indian Ocean can
be accessed at <http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/asia/mv.htm>
A map of the Laamu Atoll can be accessed at
<http://www.atolls.gov.mv/atolls.asp?atoll_letter=O>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Maldives can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=1282101&v=1.933,73.417,5>. - Mod.TY]
